How do you upgrade an EKS cluster?

High-Level Order (never skip this sequence)

1. Control Plane first
2. Add-ons second
3. Worker Nodes last

Upgrading nodes before control plane = unsupported / breaks things.

Step 1 — Upgrade Control Plane

AWS Console → EKS → Clusters → select "coreiq"
        ↓
Overview tab → Kubernetes version → click "Update now"
        ↓
Select target version (e.g. 1.29) → click "Update"
        ↓
Wait ~20 mins → status changes to "Active"
-------------------------
Step 2 — Upgrade Add-ons

EKS → Clusters → coreiq → Add-ons tab
        ↓
You'll see:  kube-proxy  |  coredns  |  vpc-cni
             "Update available" badge on each
        ↓
Click each add-on → "Edit" → select latest version → "Save changes"

How each runs

Add-on      | Type       | Why
------------|------------|---------------------------------------------------------------
kube-proxy  | DaemonSet  | Needs to run on every node — manages iptables rules per node
CoreDNS     | Deployment | Just needs to be available cluster-wide — 2 replicas, any node
vpc-cni     | DaemonSet  | Needs to run on every node — assigns pod IPs from VPC per node
---------------
Step 3 — Upgrade Worker Nodes

EKS → Clusters → coreiq → Compute tab
        ↓
Node groups section → select node group
        ↓
Click "Update now" → choose update strategy:
   • Rolling update (recommended — no downtime)
   • Force update (faster but may cause downtime)
        ↓
Confirm → AWS drains and replaces nodes one by one
-----------
Step 4 — Verify

EKS → Clusters → coreiq → Overview tab
        ↓
Check Kubernetes version shows 1.29
        ↓
Compute tab → Node groups → confirm all nodes on new version

